Is Sunscreen Destroying Coral Reefs?

Sunscreens and the toxic products it has, used to protect ourselves from UV light, can potentially harm other species and ecosystems, such as our marine life.

An estimated 14,000 tons of sunscreen is believed to be deposited in oceans annually with the greatest damage found in popular reef areas such as Hawaii and the Caribbean

One of the most threatened marine species, when it comes to harmful chemicals in sunscreen, are coral. At first glance they may appear as inanimate objects however they are invertebrates that provide the ocean's ecosystem with the basic needs to keep thriving. Without coral reefs the oceans ecosystem will not be sustained which is why it is important to protect coral reefs from dying off.

Marine Life

When we think of what the biggest ecosystem is, what do we think of? Well considering Earth is 70 percent water, the biggest ecosystem is the Ocean and the marine life it carries. Now, even though we have only explored as little as over 7 percent of the Ocean, it is still crucial to our survival. Marine life provides us with lots of resources and it is our main source of water which we need to survive. It also provides us with food and even protection from nature itself. Reefs are a super important part of our marine life, because they protect our coasts from storms and erosion. Also our oceans provide us with millions if not billions of jobs that help our economy and our people maintain themselves at level.

So why should humans care about maintaining the ocean's protection? As shown in the image above, the Ocean provides many basic needs that are beneficial to humans and Earth. The resources we are gifted from the ocean can be gone in an instance if not taken care of. Marine life, apart from being crucial to our survival and our economy, is something that we shouldn’t damage because it can cause big biological changes creating bigger problems and affecting our other ecosystems. When something like this happens the impact it can have on us since we are part of that biological chain is huge and unknown. Our trees and land animals apart from marine life can be affected and they can be extinct if we don’t start taking care of our marine life. So now the question is, what is our real impact on marine life and what is one of the biggest problems we have right now that is hurting our marine life?

Human Impact on Marine Life

Many of us are unaware of how humans are impacting Marine Life with sunscreen. Well to start I want to inform you that when individuals wash or swim while wearing sunscreen, the chemicals in the sunscreen are released into the environment, contaminating our waters. One of these chemicals is oxybenzone which is an extremely harmful chemical. This causes coral reefs to bleach due to the dangerous chemicals obtained by the sunscreen. While sunscreens protect human skin from damaging UV radiation, these advancements may harm other animals and ecosystems. I’ve always asked myself, why are coral reefs so important? According to NOAA, corals benefit people by acting as natural barriers that protect them from violent storms and waves. “Coral reefs protect coastlines from storms and erosion, provide jobs for local communities, and offer opportunities for recreation. They are also are a source of food and new medicines”, they stated. Apart from this, thousands of marine animals rely on coral reefs for refuge and safety.

In the video provided, you can see the huge difference between 2016 and 2017, and this huge difference was made in just one year. Notice how vibrant and golden the living corals were in 2016 and after a year how the living corals became dead corals with grays and greens colors. You can actually notice how the fish population diminished in the video, which might have died due to the fact that the corals are dead, and many fishes depend on coral reefs .

What is on these sunscreens?

Sunscreen can contain many toxic chemicals that do not directly affect us humans or our skins in such small quantities but it can cause extreme damage to other species when exposed to it even the smallest amount, especially coral reefs.

Oxybenzone

Oxybenzone is a UV chemical that is found very often in sunscreen lotions and it does not take much of this chemical to cause a lot of damage to both humans and the marine ecosystem.

What does this chemical actually do to our Coral Reefs? It leads to Coral Bleaching. Coral bleaching occurs when corals are exposed to different environmental stressors which causes them to expel a microscopic symbiotic algae called zooxanthellae from their tissues. Since they use this algae as their main food source, corals become more sensitive to environmental stressors and turn pale or white. Just like humans become pale when sick corals begin to bleach when stressed.

Additionally, this toxicant affects the Coral Reefs DNA which prevents reproduction and ultimately leads to their death and that of the ecosystem.

According to NOAA, constant increasing amounts of oxybenzone concentrations in water affects and damages the DNA of coral, and this prevents them not only from reproducing and therefore thriving the ecosystem but also affects their recovery from environmental disturbances such as storms, sedimentation and climate change. "The reef just stays dead until it becomes a ruin," they stated.

Octinoxate

Many sunscreens also contain Octinoxate which, although it is not harmful to humans in small portions, has the same damaging effect on coral reefs by destroying their defense against coral bleaching.

Reef-Safe Sunscreen

It’s all about buying the right sunscreens. When we buy our sunscreen, we need to make sure that it’s a “reef-safe” or “reef-friendly” bottle. But we can’t stop there, we need to always check the actual ingredients to make sure the bottle doesn’t have any of the ingredients that cause coral bleaching. The reason that we have to check ourselves is because there is no government oversight and producers are not obligated to assess if their products have an actual influence on reefs.

Oxybenzone and Octinoxate are two main ingredients to avoid. But we should also stay clear of Benzophenone-1, Benzophenone-8, OD-PABA, 4-Methylbenzylidene camphor, 3-Benzylidene camphor, and Octocrylene. These are the chemicals that can disrupt coral reproduction, damage DNA, and exacerbate the consequences of coral bleaching. The graphic below includes a great summary of what ingredients we should be avoiding when selecting our sunscreens and which ingredients we should actually be looking for, feel free to save this graphic so you have a cheat sheet you can check the next time you buy sunscreen!

Now, the next big concern that many of us have when it comes to choosing a particular sunscreen is whether we should opt for a sunscreen that has a higher SPF or one with a lower SPF. According to Dr. Craig A. Downs, Ph.D, the advantages of the earlier are exaggerated, and because it includes a larger amount of chemicals, it is really more damaging to the environment. He claims that "They don't statistically protect you anymore against UV radiation [above] SPF 30. So you just need to find a very good SPF 30 that has done the rigorous FDA-required testing for water resistance and that's usually 80 to 90 minutes, and reapply every 80 to 90 minutes".

Below you’ll find a list that we compiled of some terrific reef-safe sunscreens:

  • Thinksport SPF 50 Sunscreen
  • Kinfield Daily Dew SPF 35
  • Kokua Sun Care Hawaiian SPF 50 Natural Zinc Sunscreen
  • All Good SPF 30 Sport Sunscreen Lotion
  • Suntegrity Natural Mineral Sunscreen
  • Raw Elements SPF 30 Certified Natural Sunscreen

Since 1998, the MarineBio Conservation Society has been a nonprofit volunteer marine conservation and science education group working online together to educate the world about ocean life, marine biology, marine conservation, and a sea ethic.
